05754nam a22007335i 9780773597785DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735977857 a10.1515/97807735977852doi  a(DE-B1597)657548  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT151b.C58 2015 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.762231 aJones, Kevin Edson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCity-Regions in Prospect? :bExploring the Meeting Points between Place and Practice /cKevin Edson Jones, Rob Shields, Alex Lord. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b5 maps, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tIntroduction: City-Regions in Prospect? -- tThe City-Region: In Retrospect, in Snapshot, in Prospect -- tRe-spatializing the City as the City-Region? -- tLeaving the City-Region Behind? The Growth and Decline of Metropolitan Rescaling in Manchester, England -- tOn Wanting to Be a Global City: Global Rankings and Urban Governance in Calgary -- t“Localism” in an Age of Austerity: Inequalities and Governance Dilemmas in the Sheffield City-Region -- tOttawa: Would “Telling Its Story” Be the Way to Go? -- tCalibrating the Regional Map to Enhance City-Region Competitiveness -- tResilience and Governance in City-Regions: Lessons From Waterloo, Ontario -- tThe Environmental Governance of Canadian City-Regions: Problems, Actions, and Challenges -- tThe Tensions and Benefits of Regionalizing Palliative Care Services: Considerations for City-Regionalism -- tConclusion: Prospects? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow should the metropolis be governed? What is the appropriate scale to consider and organize local governance and communities? Bringing together an interdisciplinary and international body of scholarly work, City-Regions in Prospect? explores the city-region as both an evolving concept and as a growing area of planning practice. Contributors raise critical questions about the ways in which governance reform is being reshaped and whether current trends towards rescaling and rebounding cities actually address local challenges of urbanization and globalization. These essays highlight the tensions and uncertainties between the city-region as a concept and the experiences of local communities when municipal policies are applied. Proposing a challenge to scholars and municipal leaders to account for flexibility, adaptability to local contexts, social robustness, and community engagement, City-Regions in Prospect? Captures the growing relevance and importance of cities in a rapidly urbanizing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCities and townsvCase studies. 0aCity planningvCase studies. 0aGlobalizationvCase studies. 0aMunicipal governmentvCase studies. 0aRegionalismvCase studies. 0aUrbanizationvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAndrew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtherington, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuay, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamel, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Kevin Edson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary